Here is a final, detailed conclusion, written in clear professional English, suitable to close the incident, PIR, RCA, or management report.
Final Conclusion
The incident affecting Azure DevOps CI agents on RHEL 8 is caused by a deadlock in Podman / OCI runtime initialization triggered by Dynatrace OneAgent global injection via /etc/ld.so.preload.
On RHEL 8, Dynatrace injects liboneagentproc.so into all dynamically linked processes at load time. When Podman starts (even for non-network commands such as podman version), this preload interferes with low-level system libraries (glibc, pthread, futex) during OCI runtime initialization (runc / crun). This results in a process-level deadlock before any container execution or network communication occurs.
This explains why:
The process hangs before any request to Artifactory
The issue is 100% reproducible at the same runtime initialization stage
Network, proxy, TLS, and Artifactory are not involved
Disabling the preload immediately restores normal Podman behavior
The issue does not affect RHEL 9 systems because they use a newer and compatible userland stack (glibc, OpenSSL 3, Podman 4/5, updated OCI runtimes) that correctly handles Dynatrace instrumentation.
Local Dynatrace configuration (oneagent.conf) is not sufficient to resolve the issue because /etc/ld.so.preload is evaluated by the dynamic loader before Dynatrace configuration is applied. As long as liboneagentproc.so is referenced in /etc/ld.so.preload, Podman can deadlock on RHEL 8, even when container monitoring is logically disabled.
Final Resolution
The issue can be resolved in one of the following supported ways:
Dynatrace-level fix (recommended)
Exclude Podman and OCI runtime processes from OneAgent injection at the process-injection level for RHEL 8 CI agents.
OS-level mitigation (CI-only)
Disable Dynatrace preload injection on RHEL 8 CI agents by removing OneAgent from /etc/ld.so.preload.
Additionally, migrating CI agents from RHEL 8 to RHEL 9 permanently eliminates the issue and aligns with platform best practices.
Final Recommendation
Immediately apply Dynatrace process-level exclusions on RHEL 8 CI agents
Avoid preload-based instrumentation on CI/CD runtimes
Plan migration of CI workloads to RHEL 9
Document CI agents as non-candidates for full-stack OneAgent injection
One-Line Executive Summary
The CI outage was caused by a Dynatrace OneAgent preload incompatibility with Podman on RHEL 8, resulting in a runtime deadlock. Excluding container runtimes from Dynatrace injection or migrating to RHEL 9 fully resolves the issue.
